\begin{block}{Wifi coverage - Ignoring phase}
\blockcolours
\begin{itemize}
\item It is also important to get an idea of the power of the \textbf{wifi coverage}. 
\item This is calculated along the rays taking into account the \textbf{attenuation in free space} and the \textbf{reduction at the reflections}. 
\item The loss resulting from the distance travelled is calculated using the \textbf{Friis transmission formula}:
\begin{equation}
\label{eqn::FriisTransmissFormula}
\frac{u_r}{u_t}=G_a G_b \left( \frac{\lambda}{4 \pi r} \right)^2, \hspace{0.1\linewidth}\cite{aragon2008antennas}
\end{equation} 
where $u_r$, $u_t$ give the power at the receiver and transmitter relatively. The gain for the antenna's $G_a$ and $G_b$ are taken to be $1$. 
\item Figure \ref{fig::signalcoverage} shows the signal power for two \textbf{different transmitter locations}.
